<br>
<br>
I bring you to Kelethin, the grand city of the wood elf people and the home of a certain elf you all know. Here will I share with you the tale of her life and its joys as well as it’s woe’s. Many people have entered her life and many have left it as well. Many an adventure has she been on and as she sits in her fathers tree cottage she ponders her life and decides that she will put it to paper for future generations so that they may gather what knowledge they will from what is written within. Know you this first; among the elves all are family. What references she makes to brothers or sisters are in this regard as she was an only child to her parents.<br>
            Imagine if you will a small cottage sitting high in a tall tree lush with leaves. Imagine on the platform in front of the cottage an old worn chair and leaning against the wall next to the door an old axe that is rusty with age but bears the signs of battle long ago past. Imagine that hanging from the door is an elven dreamcatcher to bring good luck to those within and imagine if you will that within this cottage there once was a family, a mother and father and a small girl child who was doted on by her parents. Here is where we will begin our tale…..a tale of an elf and her adventures both good and bad.<br>
             She was a small child when born. Her mother was a druid and her father a warrior. They named her Keyra and loved her as any parent would love their child and her home was one filled with love and affection. As she grew her mother taught her the ways of the druids. She taught her daughter how to call to the animals and to respect the wildness of Mother Tunare for she was the Mother of all and deserved that respect. She taught her how to forage for food and how to use fire and ice to defend herself.  Her father, being a warrior in his heart always, taught her the ways of the sword and the shield. He taught her how to hide and blend into the woods, how to hunt, and how to stalk. He wanted his only child to know how to protect herself because he knew she had her mothers nature and would not stay close to home once she felt the call of the world outside their home.<br>
            Keyra spent many years at home learning from her parents. She proved to be her mother’s daughter and the ways of the druid came naturally for her. Often you could find her at the top of any of the tallest tree’s staring out at the world and wondering what was out there for her to find. But just as often you would find her engaged in some mischief somewhere with others and she occasionally got herself into trouble but all it took was a smile and a hug and her father would forgive her for whatever she had done. She practiced the arts her mother taught her and she learned spells and chants for both battle and for travel.<br>
            One night as she came home she found her father sitting at the table with a bottle of strong elven wine in front of him mostly gone and she was sure she could see the tracks of recent tears on his cheeks. She wasn’t sure how to approach her father because she had never seen him cry. It just wasn’t something warriors did and she had grown to accept this as fact.<br>
            She walked up to him and placed her hand on his shoulder, he was trembling and this worried her further. “What’s wrong papa? Why are you upset? Have I done something?” She couldn’t think of anything she had done that would have upset him even though there were a few tricks she’d played on a couple of bullies he didn’t know about but she felt sure if he had found out about it he would have only laughed at her and told her to stop picking on the boys.<br>
             Her father looked up at her and smiled. She could tell it was semi forced but said nothing. “Keyra, sit down, we must talk.” She did as he asked and began to notice that her mother was not home. Dread started to fill her as her mind started to file over the possibilities but avoiding the worst of all. He then told her that her mother was ill, that she was with the elder’s and that they were trying everything they could to find out what was wrong and cure her. She sat in disbelief as he told her how he had come home from hunting to find her unconscious and feverish. He had taken her directly to the elder’s and begged them to cure his wife. “Is she still with them?”, she asked. Her father looked at her and spoke so softly that she had to lean forward to hear him, “Aye, they say that it doesn’t look good and they are unsure she will survive the night.” Without saying a word she left the cottage and raced to Felwithe. She knew that this was where her father would have taken her mother. The high elves were reknown for their healing abilities and were said to even be able to bring back the dead if you brought he or she to them quickly enough. She raced with everything she had hoping to be able to get there in time and hoping that the clerics there would allow her to see her mother. They were set in their ways and it wasn’t often they allowed a stranger to witness their workings.<br>
             She reached Felwithe’s gates and raced within heedless of the guards and those who passed in and out of the city. When she reached the cleric’s hall she banged on the door and begged the man who answered the door to let her in. After explaining who she was and why she was at their door he let her enter and asked her to follow him. She did as he asked and followed him through halls that were brightly lit and the very walls seemed to speak out in welcome to her. Awe filled her as she looked at the engravings on the walls as she followed the cleric in front of her. He came to a stop in front of a large wooden door and she could hear low chanting coming from behind it. He warned her that anything she saw here must be kept secret and to make sure that she adhered to any rules they gave her inside. She nodded her understanding and followed him inside when he opened the door and beckoned her to follow him.<br>
               Inside she saw a gathering of robed clerics standing in what looked to be a circle. As she slowly walked up closer she saw that they were surrounding what looked to be a bed. The cleric she had followed here walked up to the oldest and whispered something in his ear glancing at her as he did. The elder turned slowly and acknowledged her with a smile. “Enter child, you are welcome here. I only wish that the tidings which bring you here were of a happier occasion.” He beckoned her forward and as she walked towards him she realized it was her mother they surrounded. She was lying on the bed and was tossing her head back and forth her face covered in sweat. Tears began to flow from her eyes as she sat next to her mother and took her hand in her own. She gasped at the heat coming from her mothers hand and she felt her forehead and groaned aloud when she felt how hot her mothers fever truly was. Keyra leaned down next to her and whispered in her ear, “Mama.. i’m here, everything’s going to be ok. Mama, can you hear me? Mama..?” T’was here that the elder touched her shoulder and spoke softly.” Your mother is very ill child. She passes in and out of consciousness but she spoke of something I would talk with you about. Please.. come with me so we can speak.”<br>
            Keyra blinked back her tears and humbly followed the elder cleric stealing glances back at her mother while she followed him into a side room. The clerics had resumed their chanting and surrounded her again. She said several silent prayers to Tunare begging Her to heal her mother of whatever made her so ill. The elder shut the door when she entered behind him and motioned to an empty chair at a table. She sat and he sat across from her after he fetched a bottle of wine and two goblets. He filled both goblets and handed one to her. She took it and drank it quickly seeking to numb herself. After drinking a second to steel her nerves she looked at the cleric. “What is wrong with her? Why is she so ill? Every day I see my mother and she has not been sick, I don’t understand!”<br>
           “Your mother spoke to me before the fever got worse.”, He told her. “She spoke of a quest she had been on and that only your father had known of it. She said that she was supposed to best a great evil that had been sinking into the land and that she had met this foe and lost. She fears for her soul and wishes you to continue your druidly studies so that you may face this foe yourself one day and hopefully be better learned and emerge victorious.” His face suddenly looked so old to her and she wondered how many years he had spent here healing the ill and the dying. “What am I supposed to do? Who will teach me if my mother doesn’t recover?” No one but her mother had ever taught her anything of the druids and she felt she would be lost without her to show her all the things she didn’t know.<br>
           He got up then and walked to a large cabinet. He opened it and from it he withdrew a scimitar. Handing it to her he spoke, “Take this ..” he told her. “ You must go out into the world. There is nothing more for you to learn from books and scrolls. Now you must learn from experience. It’s time for you to find your own now. You are welcome to remain here with your mother until she has passed.”<br>
           She spent the next month with her mother bathing her and caring for her as she died slowly. Whatever it was that was taking her did it slowly. It was as if her mother had been poisoned and was being eaten slowly from within. On the last day her mother was alive she held her until she died and then taking the scimitar the old cleric had given her she returned home. She told her father everything that had happened and asked him to make sure that her mother had a druid funeral. Then she kissed her father on his head and wished him well promising to return soon. She just couldn’t stay in Kelethin with all the memories she had. It was time for her to leave the tree city and go see the world. Inside her heart she promised her mother that she would find the person who had caused her death and make sure that they met one just as painful.<br>
