The sun was shining down on Keyra as she sat on the deck of the boat and watched the water silently thinking to herself. After she left Kelethin she had gone back to Felwithe and spoken with the Elder again. He had told her to begin her quest in Freeport across the sea in Antonica. She replayed their conversation in her mind and thought about the things he had said to her.<br>
<br>
“Where do I begin Elder? I don’t know who or what I’m looking for and I have little faith that I will be able to accomplish this task you put before me.” She had sat in a chair staring into a cup of elven wine and the sense of hopelessness was obvious on her face.<br>
<br>
“Go to Freeport child. Seek out the rogues and the shadow knights. They know of this evil and not all of them side with it. There you will be able to find someone to aid you in your quest.” He had the younger priests help her fill her packs with provisions and sent her on her way with as much wisdom as he could. “Be careful and be smart. Trust no one until they’ve proven otherwise. Should anyone who follows this evil find out what you’re about they WILL attempt to stop you. You may face much danger child but if you hold true and doubt yourself not you will succeed and avenge your mother well!”<br>
<br>
Sipping on one of the flasks of water the priests had provided her she sat and wondered what this “friend” would look like. Would they be trustworthy? Would she be able to tell them everything and have them follow her? She decided she would follow the Elder’s advice and keep the important information to herself until she knew for sure if this person could be trusted. “Hell first I have to find them….” She thought to herself.<br>
<br>
Some time later the boat docked in Freeport and as she walked off the boat ramp she looked about her and marveled at the size of the town. “How am I supposed to find anything or anyone here? I’ll be searching until I’m old and grey and sipping on berry juice.” Sighing she heaved her pack onto her shoulder and walked into town. The noises were almost too much for her ears. Everywhere she walked there were merchants yelling out to passersby to come and look at their wares. She passed an inn where a tall burly man tossed a drunk out into the street barely missing her as she dodged the drunkard. On one side she passed a smithy working in front of his shop as he banged away at metal with his hammer and on her other side she passed what looked to be a leather shop where a woman was hanging what looked to be a fresh animal pelt on the outside wall of her shop, stretching it to dry in the sun. An old man stopped her and shoving jewelry in her face told her how his baubles were the cheapest in town and the best of quality. Shoving him aside she moved on.A small child ran up to her and stopped her.. “Please miss, buy one of my cinnamon sticks? Only 5 copper!” Smiling at the boy child she handed him several gold coins after she noticed his dirty face and torn clothes. “Thank ye miss!” he cried as he ran off with the coins she’d given him and she nibbled on the cinnamon sticks she had bought from him. “Not as good as grandmothers but not entirely bad… ” she thought to herself. Smiling she began to enjoy her surroundings a little and walked on down the street taking everything in, nibbling as she went.<br>
<br>
Keyra was indeed impressed with the large city but it still wasn’t anywhere near as grand to her as Kelethin. Walking on she eventually noticed some alleyways off to her left and remembering what the Elder had told her she decided to venture forth and have a look around. Stopping to pull the hood of her cloak over her head she wandered down what looked to be the busiest alleyway keeping her head down a bit so as not to attract attention and she pulled her cloak about her. At the end of the alley there was a sort of courtyard where she spotted an Inn and several shops. Wandering about were drunkards and what she could only assume were what her father had always called “wenches”, women clothed in low cut dresses and fluffed up hair and she watched as they spoke to men as they wandered by them offering the men their “attentions” in exchange for coin. “I can see why the Elder told me to be careful…. a person could lose their purse here quickly if they weren’t careful…” she thought to herself. Pulling her hood down a little lower she walked towards the Inn and after taking a moment to gather her courage she walked in and immediately noticed the smell of old ale and sweat that seemed to have permeated every inch of the place. “Disgusting!” she mumbled. Walking to a table that sat in the corner of the main room away from the rest she sat down and waited for a barmaid to come and see what she wanted.<br>
<br>
“Wine please. And some bread and cheese.” Tossing a few gold coins onto the table she sat back as the barmaid hurriedly picked up the coins and rushed off to get her the food and wine. Looking around she noticed that she wasn’t the only one in the Inn trying to look invisible. Several tables had people sitting at them with lowered hoods and shadowed faces. “Mother Tunare what have I gotten myself into?” she wondered. “How am I supposed to find anyone trustworthy in this mess of thieves and cut-throats?” <br>
<br>
When the barmaid returned with her wine and food she stopped her for a minute. “Pardon me but where would I go if I were looking to find or hire someone to help me with a quest? Someone who would earn their coin and not slit my throat for it?” <br>
<br>
“Ah well .. ” the barmaid said. “You’ll not find a lot of honest folk in this part of the town miss but over in the other corner there is a young woman who wandered into town a few days ago and said she was looking for work. I’m judging by her sword and armor underneath her cloak that she ain’t lookin’ to wash dishes if you gather my meanin’. Looks like she could hold her own against any of the filth that comes around ‘ere.”<br>
<br>
Thanking her Keyra slipped the barmaid a few more gold coins for the information and then began to watch the woman she had pointed out while sipping her wine and snacking on the cheese and stale bread.” How to approach her?” she wondered. Even a barmaid could mistake someone for being honest when they may very well be the wickedest. Keyra had no desire to get her throat slit or her purse or belongings stolen when she’d only been in town but a day. Watching the cloaked woman she observed her manners and clothing. She wore a very dark cloak with a large hood that covered her face except for her nose and below. When she turned her cloak fluttered enough to reveal what looked to Keyra to be some kind of plate armor beneath and she disserned that the pointed bulge at the back of her cloak must have been her weapon, a sword no doubt. She had seen warrior women in Kelethin, this wasn’t a surprise to her. In fact some of the best warriors she had known growing up were female. The woman carried herself with a grace that belied her for a Lady and Keyra decided that she must be from noble birth and that whatever her tale was it would undoubtedly be interesting. Picking up the tray of food and her bottle of wine she walked over to the table where this woman sat and setting them down spoke to the cloaked figure. “Hail m’lady..may I sit with you?”<br>
<br>
“If that’s your wish, it’s no business of mine unless you want to share that wine you have there and I wouldn’t be remiss of some of your cheese as well.” Smiling Keyra sat down next to her and sliding her hood back abit introduced herself. “I am Keyra Krystalin of Kelethin, tree city of the wood elves. Who would you be if I may ask?” <br>
<br>
“Not that it’s any of your business but my name is Aoladari Raveynfyre and I am a shadow knight and from where is none of your concern.” The woman glanced up at Keyra with hard eyes and for a moment Keyra was positive she had made a very large mistake in coming over here. “I am told your sword is for hire. I may have a quest for you that would not only fill your purse but you would be looked apon by many with reverence as well as respect.” <br>
<br>
“What care I for respect? What does any shadow knight care about the whimsical rantings of any elf? Everyone knows your kind are partial to fantasy and fairy tales.” Sitting back Aoladari moved one side of her cloak back to reveal her sword and Keyra saw that it was a fine weapon indeed, decorated with small jewels and engraved apon the blade in what looked to be some form of elvish though she felt certain it was probably of the dark elves since she couldn’t read the writing at all. “I am a druid “ she told her “and I am on a quest that requires a sword to help me on the way and a brain behind that sword capable of intelligent thought and I wouldn’t mind someone with manners either!” Sitting back Keyra sipped from the bottle of wine and hoped like hell that her idea worked instead of getting her killed and got the shadow knights attention.<br>
<br>
Glancing at Keyra and sizing her up Aoladari slowly began to smirk. “Well I see you have a tongue to rival perhaps even mine. Allright then,I have a room upstairs. Bring your wine with you and we’ll go discuss just what your quest is and what it would require of me before I tell you what it’ll cost you and that’s if I even agree to help you in the first place mind you..” Getting up Aoladari walked towards a flight of stairs and Keyra followed her saying many silent prayers to Tunare that she wasn’t about to enter a trap.<br>
<br>
“Mother Tunare please help me, I hope this woman’s as trustworthy as I need her to be…” And with that she walked into Aoladari’s room behind her and sat down in a chair. “first let me tell you a tale of how I can to be so far from home…” And with that leaving out some parts she told Aoladari how she came to be in Freeport.<br>
