Aoladari didn't know what to think of this druid who had approached her. All she knew is that this woman must be despirate to be asking strangers in an inn for help with her task.<br>
<br>
Once the druid named Keyra had told her story, Aoladari sat back and thought about the issue at hand. Money had not been fourthcoming in recent times. Aoladari had given up fighting for her food, so to speak. She had just become sick of it all and was honestly copperless after this evening's dinner. Aoladari had no tradeskills with which she could make more money, and this seemed to her like a way out of her growing debt.<br>
<br>
&quot;I will accept your offer, with a few conditions,&quot; Aoladari said. &quot;My room and board must be taken care of on top of the sum you have offered me, starting tonight. Also.. when I tell you not to ask about something that will be the end of it. There will be no questions about my actions in front of others. If you wish to question me in private, you may, but I will not promise an answer.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Druidess thought about this for a moment, and then agreed to the bargan.<br>
<br>
&quot;Where do we start then? Have you heard of what I speak of?&quot; Keyra asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have heard mumblings in the tunnels of Freeport, but most know that I am not a true Shadowknight. I offered my services to many in the past whom my Guildleaders are not appreciative of. Helping you in this way is certainly an example of that! A true Shadowknight might have beheaded you downstairs and then robbed you of your belongings, fair lady, you need to be more careful.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Certainly you have helped those people for a good reason then. I see something in you that most humans do not carry these days,&quot; Keyra said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Indeed. Many a year ago, probably before your parents were even an itch in their daddy's leggings, my ancestry was &quot;blessed&quot;, as some have said, with the Lucan line. Sir Lucan's grandfather had an escapade with my barwench of a grandmother, and he as we all know is part of the leadership of Freeport. Since  I was a part of this kindred I felt a leaning towards knighthood, but alas, they would have none of me.. and evil was all who would accept me.&quot;<br>
<br>
Keyra started to see why she had seen potential in this girl, and felt sorry for her in the same way she felt sorry for the small boy in the marketplace.<br>
<br>
&quot;But, back to your issue. The evil you speak of was cast many a moon ago by the necromancers of Erudin. They have a mastery over evil like none other, and there would be our best place to start.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Do you have a room for the night Aola? May I call you Aola?&quot; Keyra asked.<br>
<br>
Aoladari grinned at the use of her nickname, &quot;I do, though I had been planning a visit to an old friend, and possibly finding some work there, but since it was unannounced I can hold that off for later. And yes, you may call me Aola.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Then I will go downstairs and make sure they understand that my payment will be for us both. Do you mind sharing this room?&quot; Keyra asked, looking at the second bed with all of the scrolls and backpacks on it.<br>
<br>
&quot;No, but let me warn you, fair druid, should you try anything I do know how to use this-&quot; Aoladari pointed to her sword. &quot;I may not be the best in the land, but there are few who can deny my prowess.&quot; Aoladari had made her point it seemed, since Keyra was turning a sickly shade of yellow and had obviously gulped at the thought of betrayal, on either side.<br>
<br>
&quot;I u-u-understand your feelings.&quot; Keyra said as she slipped out of the room.<br>
<br>
Aoladari had wanted no more than something this.... opportune to fall in her lap. She was however suspicious that the dealings ahead were not going to be easy, nothing like collecting orc scalps as she had done in her younger years. she pondered how to go about asking Marl Kastane about the evil she had only heard rumblings of in the tunnels.<br>
<br>
*Why did everyone have to stop talking about this right after she entered the tunnels?? Damnit this could be so much easier if only--- No I will not think of that, the past is the past,* Aoladari thought to herself.<br>
<br>
Keyra closed the door to the room, leaned on it heavily, and breathed a sigh of relief. She had certainly understood Aoladari's &quot;point&quot; when she said those last words.<br>
