<br>
After paying the Innkeeper for their room she went back up and entering the room saw Aola sitting on her bed sharpening her sword. Putting her pack on her bed she unbuckled her scimitar and set it with her pack. “I need to go out for some air Aola. I will be back before dawn and then we can decide where we will begin our search.” Tossing Aola a small bag of coins she smiled at her. “This is yours, with luck when we have reached the end of our quest there will be more for you as I’m sure you’ll earn it and then some before we’re done.” Aola opened the small pouch and looking at the coins within smiled, at least she wouldn’t be hungry for a while. She watched as Keyra left the room with nothing but her cloak and to what would have been Keyra’s surprise thought the same things of her that she had pondered about Aola not long ago in the hallway.<br>
<br>
As she stepped outside and began to head to the towns gates Keyra heard music and singing coming from a large clearing. There was a large crowd gathered around what looked like a stage and she ventured closer to get a peek. There was a woman on the stage and her voice sounded like an angel’s to Keyra’s ears. She was a half elf Keyra thought and she had an ominous beauty to her. As she watched her sing Keyra noticed a man to the side of the stage. In his cloak he was almost invisible, yes Keyra wouldn’t have even noticed him she thought if she hadn’t glanced in that direction. She turned her attention back to the bard on the stage and couldn’t help tapping her feet a bit to the lively tune the bard was belting out. Then she felt a prickling on the back of her neck and she would have sworn she felt as though someone were staring at her. Pulling the hood of her cloak up more to cover her face she glanced around to try and see who it was or if her mind was just playing tricks on her. As she glanced around she noticed that the cloaked man next to the stage was the one staring at her and she shuddered. “Who is he and why is he staring at me?” As she started to turn to walk away she was certain she saw the bard glance at her and wink. <br>
<br>
Feeling like a toy in a child’s nursery she walked away quickly and headed for the town gates. As she left the town she hid her cloak in the trunk of a tall tree and after thanking it for guarding her cloak she then began to run. As she ran she chanted the words her mother had taught her and a soft glow encompassed her as her formed changed and what was an elf running in the night became a dark wolf. She howled as she ran reveling in the feeling of the night wind in her fur and the smells of the night air. This was one of the talents her mother had taught her that she loved the most. Running through the tree’s she howled again and smiled inside as she heard the wolves answer her with their howls. Then she heard a howl that stood out from the rest. Heading towards it she howled again and when she heard the answer she knew who it was. God but she hadn’t seen her in so long! Running with everything she had she came to the crest of a hill and sitting there was a wolf with fur dark like her own and she moved forward to nuzzle the other wolf before taking her own form again and smiling at it. The wolf seemed to smile as it stood up and after nuzzling Keyra’s hand took its true form and a human stood before Keyra. She smiled and greeted her. “Sorchae! Sister mine! It’s been a long time and it’s very good to see you again!” Stepping forward she hugged Sorchae tightly. It had been a long time, since they were children. Sorchae had spent some time in Kelethin learning the skills of druids for a time when she was young and she and Keyra had formed a quick and strong friendship. Much of Keyra’s mischief had been while she was with Sorchae for they both had a wild streak in them that was only matched by the others. “What are you doing out here?”<br>
<br>
“I could ask you the same thing, this is a long way from Kelethin!” Sorchae smiled at Keyra and returned the hug. “My lust for travel hasn’t dwindled any and I love being out here in the woods where I can relax. Towns are too noisy and cluttered for me. I would rather be out here.” They walked together talking for a while and caught up on old times and Keyra told Sorchae all about her mother and what had happened to bring her here. “Sis I am sorry, I will keep my ears open and listen for anything that might be of help to you.”  Keyra hugged her tightly before saying her goodbyes and explaining that she had to return and she told Sorchae about Aola and their bargain. ”Be careful Keyra, she is still a shadow knight no matter what you may or may not perceive about her.” Smiling and hugging once more Keyra took her wolf form again and ran back towards Freeport stopping at the tree where she had hidden her cloak. After putting it on she slipped back into the town and headed for the Inn never noticing the eyes that had watched her from underneath a tall tree and that had seen her leave earlier and now watched her re-enter the town. <br>
